	<item>
		<title>By: Robb Bryant</title>
		<link>http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/bass-tips/13-essential-audition-tips-for-bass-players.html#comment-16553</link>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Robb Bryant]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sat, 10 Oct 2015 01:23:00 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/?p=11958#comment-16553</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[I&#039;ve been playing for 27 years and been in a few bands and played lots of gigs. I think an important part of the prep for playing in a band is to have a good chat with the guy who&#039;s contact you in the first place. Don&#039;t just text or email, pick up the phone and talk. You&#039;ll get a good feel of the vibe. I&#039;d also add that to try and enjoy yourself with the music will also help. OK, you may not get the gig, but that&#039;s not necessarily your fault, so don&#039;t take it personally. Just enjoy the music and the fact you&#039;re (hopefully) getting to play alongside some semi / professional musicians. Sometimes, your enjoyment of the music can carry you through the odd duff note. Oh, and be prepared to adapt. I&#039;ve gone to auditions / try-outs where we&#039;ve gone through the 3-4 tunes and the band enthusiastically want to get on with more. I&#039;d say listen to the unexpected songs and give it a go. That goes a long way with bands, especially originals bands or bands on tight, busy schedules. 

My last audition had the band leader - the lead guitarist / lead vocalist - giving hand signals to quieten down, leaning back to tell us to open up, pointing a finger in the air quickly to signify a song&#039;s ending, holding his pick up a little to signify he&#039;s about to get the audience involved. So, be prepared to adapt your playing on the spot and improvise if necessary. At the end of the rehearsal he said &quot;we want you to start a week on Friday, there&#039;s about 30 songs in the set and I&#039;ll throw a few others in depending on the crowd&quot;. That was about 3 months ago and we&#039;re flat out busy, fully booked into the first half of 2016. At a number of gigs, I&#039;ve played songs on the spot for the first time, so adaptability is the watch word. You can really help yourself by chatting to other band members and asking what songs may come up, etc.

Biggest fear isn&#039;t rejection or failure - don&#039;t be afraid of failure or you&#039;ll never try anything. The biggest fear of mine is disappointing people. I got my last audition on word of mouth, a text out of the blue and phone call asking me to audition. Somebody, somewhere had &#039;bigged me up&#039; as it were. So that last thing I wanted to do was a) make the an idiot out of the guy who referred me and b) give the guys that sinking feeling. So, I take pride in what I do, I prep as much as possible and I try to accommodate what a band wants as far as possible. 

Thanks for reading]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I&#8217;ve been playing for 27 years and been in a few bands and played lots of gigs. I think an important part of the prep for playing in a band is to have a good chat with the guy who&#8217;s contact you in the first place. Don&#8217;t just text or email, pick up the phone and talk. You&#8217;ll get a good feel of the vibe. I&#8217;d also add that to try and enjoy yourself with the music will also help. OK, you may not get the gig, but that&#8217;s not necessarily your fault, so don&#8217;t take it personally. Just enjoy the music and the fact you&#8217;re (hopefully) getting to play alongside some semi / professional musicians. Sometimes, your enjoyment of the music can carry you through the odd duff note. Oh, and be prepared to adapt. I&#8217;ve gone to auditions / try-outs where we&#8217;ve gone through the 3-4 tunes and the band enthusiastically want to get on with more. I&#8217;d say listen to the unexpected songs and give it a go. That goes a long way with bands, especially originals bands or bands on tight, busy schedules. </p>
<p>My last audition had the band leader &#8211; the lead guitarist / lead vocalist &#8211; giving hand signals to quieten down, leaning back to tell us to open up, pointing a finger in the air quickly to signify a song&#8217;s ending, holding his pick up a little to signify he&#8217;s about to get the audience involved. So, be prepared to adapt your playing on the spot and improvise if necessary. At the end of the rehearsal he said &#8220;we want you to start a week on Friday, there&#8217;s about 30 songs in the set and I&#8217;ll throw a few others in depending on the crowd&#8221;. That was about 3 months ago and we&#8217;re flat out busy, fully booked into the first half of 2016. At a number of gigs, I&#8217;ve played songs on the spot for the first time, so adaptability is the watch word. You can really help yourself by chatting to other band members and asking what songs may come up, etc.</p>
<p>Biggest fear isn&#8217;t rejection or failure &#8211; don&#8217;t be afraid of failure or you&#8217;ll never try anything. The biggest fear of mine is disappointing people. I got my last audition on word of mouth, a text out of the blue and phone call asking me to audition. Somebody, somewhere had &#8216;bigged me up&#8217; as it were. So that last thing I wanted to do was a) make the an idiot out of the guy who referred me and b) give the guys that sinking feeling. So, I take pride in what I do, I prep as much as possible and I try to accommodate what a band wants as far as possible. </p>
<p>Thanks for reading</p>
]]></content:encoded>
