		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/?p=11958#comment-16549</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Hi Scott, thanks per tips! I would like to add on more suggestion: if you have more than one bass or amp (as most of bass players...) bring with you the gear you feel &quot;the main gear&quot;. I have 6 basses hanged on the wall but most of the time I use my trusted Jazz Bass, I will never bring to an audition my 5 string fretless bass which I use few time in a month. Amp: I have an Aguilar head Db751 and a small Ampeg combo. To audition i bring always the small combo cause it&#039;s easy to plug, lighter, and you&#039;ll be ready in 30 seconds... just plug 1 cable and it&#039;s done. Furthermore you&#039;ll not lost concentration on gear setting up. You shall be focus on playing! Leave pedal effects at home. Off course for the gig I bring with me the powerful Aguilar stack and all my effects :)]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Hi Scott, thanks per tips! I would like to add on more suggestion: if you have more than one bass or amp (as most of bass players&#8230;) bring with you the gear you feel &#8220;the main gear&#8221;. I have 6 basses hanged on the wall but most of the time I use my trusted Jazz Bass, I will never bring to an audition my 5 string fretless bass which I use few time in a month. Amp: I have an Aguilar head Db751 and a small Ampeg combo. To audition i bring always the small combo cause it&#8217;s easy to plug, lighter, and you&#8217;ll be ready in 30 seconds&#8230; just plug 1 cable and it&#8217;s done. Furthermore you&#8217;ll not lost concentration on gear setting up. You shall be focus on playing! Leave pedal effects at home. Off course for the gig I bring with me the powerful Aguilar stack and all my effects :)</p>
]]></content:encoded>
