		<title>By: Mr Fretbuzz</title>
		<link>http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/bass-tips/13-essential-audition-tips-for-bass-players.html#comment-16547</link>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Mr Fretbuzz]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Thu, 08 Oct 2015 17:58:00 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/?p=11958#comment-16547</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Great lesson thanks Scott. Ive been playing for 3 years. I&#039;ve not had audition and I&#039;ve been in 6 bands, all of which have been a disaster. The first one gave me a set list of about 30 songs and they said they knew half of them. I spent 9 months learning 15 or so to the actual recordings but it was a train crash as the other guys didn&#039;t know the songs themselves and wanted to do it their way but never said what that was. We had 2 hours practice in 9 months together.  2 bands fell through without even meeting and the last one was getting there but the drummer threw his toys out of the pram about listening to tracks on my iPad in practice when the guitarist didn&#039;t have a clue about the song structure etc. Just trying to be helpful.  Result: 6 bands and not one gig.

 I have had 3 gigs at BIMM Summer Schools in Bristol and Manchester learning 4 tracks in 4 days and performing them on stage at the end of the week. At one school I was the only bass player so I played 4 songs in 3 bands on the Fruday. 12 songs in a row and that was great :-) Got to play on stage with Steve White and had a 2 hour 1-1 lesson with Yolanda Charles. At Manchester I was the oldest at 57 and had a 10 year old Spanish guitarist who knew his part. 

 I normally make TAB sheets or notes and work out the song structure, then play it over and over to the actual recording on an ampeg scr di headphone pedal...for hours and hours until I&#039;ve nailed it. For my Trinity Grade 4 exam, I played 3 songs over 2000 times before the exam. For me it&#039;s all about repeating it till nailed. The good thing about summer school is that everyone learns their parts to the actual recording.

The thing which freaks me out about bands is, as you say, a ridiculous ask to know a long set list. I&#039;m having a break and uploading my bass playing to actual tracks on utube and I&#039;ve got over 110 videos up under my channel UKFlamesey. It&#039;s a sort of portfolio I can refer people to and might help or avoid an audition lol. No issues with the other band members not knowing their parts! It&#039;s fun being part of the Beatles or whatever.

I&#039;m thinking of doing 2 weeks summer school with Berklee Valencia next year but I know deep down I need to find a good band to improve. ]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Great lesson thanks Scott. Ive been playing for 3 years. I&#8217;ve not had audition and I&#8217;ve been in 6 bands, all of which have been a disaster. The first one gave me a set list of about 30 songs and they said they knew half of them. I spent 9 months learning 15 or so to the actual recordings but it was a train crash as the other guys didn&#8217;t know the songs themselves and wanted to do it their way but never said what that was. We had 2 hours practice in 9 months together.  2 bands fell through without even meeting and the last one was getting there but the drummer threw his toys out of the pram about listening to tracks on my iPad in practice when the guitarist didn&#8217;t have a clue about the song structure etc. Just trying to be helpful.  Result: 6 bands and not one gig.</p>
<p> I have had 3 gigs at BIMM Summer Schools in Bristol and Manchester learning 4 tracks in 4 days and performing them on stage at the end of the week. At one school I was the only bass player so I played 4 songs in 3 bands on the Fruday. 12 songs in a row and that was great :-) Got to play on stage with Steve White and had a 2 hour 1-1 lesson with Yolanda Charles. At Manchester I was the oldest at 57 and had a 10 year old Spanish guitarist who knew his part. </p>
<p> I normally make TAB sheets or notes and work out the song structure, then play it over and over to the actual recording on an ampeg scr di headphone pedal&#8230;for hours and hours until I&#8217;ve nailed it. For my Trinity Grade 4 exam, I played 3 songs over 2000 times before the exam. For me it&#8217;s all about repeating it till nailed. The good thing about summer school is that everyone learns their parts to the actual recording.</p>
<p>The thing which freaks me out about bands is, as you say, a ridiculous ask to know a long set list. I&#8217;m having a break and uploading my bass playing to actual tracks on utube and I&#8217;ve got over 110 videos up under my channel UKFlamesey. It&#8217;s a sort of portfolio I can refer people to and might help or avoid an audition lol. No issues with the other band members not knowing their parts! It&#8217;s fun being part of the Beatles or whatever.</p>
<p>I&#8217;m thinking of doing 2 weeks summer school with Berklee Valencia next year but I know deep down I need to find a good band to improve. </p>
